  <content>
    <title>Figma vs Adobe Strategy 2026</title>

    <summary>Methodology for selecting or recommending between Figma and Adobe Creative Cloud for product design teams in 2026 — using a weighted decision matrix scored against team use case, AI features, developer handoff, asset creation, enterprise security, and cost. The dominant pattern for mid-size product teams is Figma (UI/UX + dev handoff) + Adobe Firefly (generative imagery).</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Tool selection decisions are high-stakes and hard to reverse once library investment grows. Agents frequently give stale recommendations (Adobe XD as a current option — it was deprecated in 2023) or underestimate migration costs. A structured, human-verified analysis against weighted criteria prevents lock-in surprises and cost misestimates. Public pricing is list price only; enterprise negotiations differ by 30 to 50 percent.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Recommending toolchain selection for a new product team (Figma, Adobe, or hybrid)</item>
        <item>Evaluating whether to migrate from one platform to the other given team size and use case</item>
        <item>Producing a design tool cost analysis (per-seat vs Creative Cloud bundle)</item>
        <item>Advising enterprise clients on vendor lock-in risk and interoperability strategy</item>
        <item>Auditing an existing recommendation document or pitch deck for stale tool references</item>
        <item>Building a request for proposal (RFP) section comparing design platform vendors</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Solo freelancer doing print/video production — Adobe wins on output formats, no analysis needed</item>
        <item>Tool selection for 3D/motion-heavy work — Blender/After Effects are the real alternatives</item>
        <item>Teams already deeply committed to one platform with significant library investment — switching cost will almost always favor staying</item>
        <item>Pure code-first design system (Storybook + Tailwind only) where no visual canvas tool is required</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="strategic-positioning">
      <p>Understanding the core positioning of each platform clarifies which teams they serve best and what tradeoffs to expect.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Figma — end-to-end product development platform; AI-driven design + prototyping; developer handoff via Dev Mode + Variables; API-first; per-seat pricing</item>
        <item>Adobe Creative Cloud — content creation powerhouse; Firefly generative AI across all apps; enterprise licensing; multimedia production (print, video, illustration)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="key-differentiators-2026">
      <p>Several differentiators stand out in 2026 and should heavily influence recommendations:</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Evaluate Figma's developer handoff (Dev Mode + Variables) as the decisive differentiator for product teams in 2026.</statement>
        <rationale>Dev Mode and Variables are the primary reason product teams choose Figma over Adobe for UI/UX work; no equivalent exists in Creative Cloud.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Do not recommend Adobe XD as a current product. Adobe XD was deprecated in 2023; the current Adobe alternatives are Adobe Express and the broader Creative Cloud apps.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents frequently recommend Adobe XD as a current option — this is incorrect; recommending a deprecated product undermines credibility.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="bad" title="Stale recommendation mentioning Adobe XD">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Team Recommendation:
For collaborative UI design, choose Adobe XD or Figma. XD offers better integration with Photoshop workflows...
        ]]></code>
        <note>Adobe XD was deprecated in 2023. Correct to: "For collaborative UI design, choose Figma or Adobe Creative Cloud apps with Firefly..."</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="dominant-hybrid-pattern">
      <p>Adobe Firefly for generative imagery + Figma as the collaborative canvas is the dominant hybrid pattern for mid-size product teams doing both UI/UX and marketing asset creation.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Separate "UI product design" (Figma leads) from "marketing asset creation" (Adobe leads) when advising teams with both needs.</statement>
        <rationale>Hybrid is often the right call for teams that do both; recommending one platform for all use cases forces tradeoffs that the hybrid avoids.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Hybrid recommendation for product + marketing team">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Recommendation: Figma for collaborative UI/UX and developer handoff. Adobe Creative Cloud (Photoshop + Illustrator) with Firefly subscription for marketing asset creation and brand image generation.

Cost: Figma (per-seat) + Adobe CC Creative Cloud (shared seats for marketing) = ~$50-70/person/month for product team, ~$30-40 for marketing contributors.
        ]]></code>
        <note>This splits responsibilities cleanly: Figma handles product iteration speed; Adobe handles creative output flexibility.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Recommending a single tool for teams with diverse needs (product designers, marketers, illustrators) and hoping "integrations" will bridge the gaps.</description>
        <reason>Forcing one tool on a team with both UI/UX and asset creation needs creates friction on both sides — product designers wait on render performance in Adobe, creatives struggle with Figma's simpler vector tools. Hybrid with a clear responsibility split is almost always more productive.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="lock-in-risk-and-migration">
      <p>Lock-in is one of the least appreciated costs in design tooling decisions. Once a team invests in component libraries and design systems, switching platforms becomes extremely expensive.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Quantify Figma library lock-in before recommending migration. Figma component libraries are not portable without significant rebuild.</statement>
        <rationale>Component library migration from Figma requires rebuilding every component in the target tool; this cost is systematically underestimated and frequently reverses migration decisions.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Decision Matrix Methodology: score each platform on weighted criteria using the canonical weights below. Adjust weights to team context before scoring.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Real-time collaboration (25 percent)</item>
        <item>AI-assisted UI design (20 percent)</item>
        <item>Developer handoff (20 percent)</item>
        <item>Asset/image generation (15 percent)</item>
        <item>Print/brand production (10 percent)</item>
        <item>Enterprise security/SSO (10 percent)</item>
      </list>
      <p>Weight allocation must be adjusted per team context before scoring.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="enterprise-requirements">
      <p>Enterprise deployments require verification beyond the feature comparison.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Audit SSO, SCIM provisioning, and data residency requirements before enterprise recommendations. Both platforms differ significantly on these dimensions.</statement>
        <rationale>Enterprise security and compliance requirements can disqualify a platform entirely regardless of feature score; these must be verified before presenting a recommendation.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Require human verification of all pricing figures before presenting to finance. Agent-generated cost calculations use list pricing; enterprise pricing is negotiated and can differ by 30 to 50 percent.</statement>
        <rationale>Presenting list pricing as enterprise pricing is a frequent cause of stakeholder distrust in tool recommendations.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-limitations">
      <p>When generating recommendations via LLM agents, be aware of these persistent failure modes:</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent comparison includes Adobe XD as a current product.</description>
        <reason>Adobe XD was deprecated in 2023; correct to Adobe Express or Creative Cloud apps. This is a persistent agent error that must be explicitly checked.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent makes feature parity claims without citing a verifiable source and date.</description>
        <reason>Feature parity claims (e.g., "Figma now matches Adobe in vector tools") are frequently inaccurate by the time an agent is queried; require human fact-check against current product pages.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent underestimates migration effort for large Figma component libraries with complex variable/token structures.</description>
        <reason>Agents have no reliable model of Figma library migration complexity; always require a human estimate based on actual component and variable counts.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents underestimate the time and cost of hybrid workflow integration (Figma + Adobe + asset pipeline coordination).</description>
        <reason>Hybrid setups sound pragmatic but add integration friction (file naming, export standards, team communication overhead, tool-switching context loss) that agents systematically underestimate.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <how-to>
      <p>Follow these steps in order. Do not skip step 1 (intake) — every later decision depends on it.</p>
      <step>Intake. Capture team size, role mix (UI/UX, brand, marketing, illustration, video), per-seat or annual budget, target launch date, current tool stack, and existing component-library size in components and variables.</step>
      <step>Trigger check. Confirm the situation matches a when-to-use case. If it matches a when-not-to-use case, stop and document why this methodology does not apply.</step>
      <step>Weight calibration. Start from the canonical weights (25/20/20/15/10/10) and adjust per team context. Document each delta with a one-line reason. Weights MUST sum to 100.</step>
      <step>Scoring. For each criterion, assign Figma and Adobe a 1-5 score. Cite a source (vendor docs, recent review, hands-on test) for each score. Compute weighted totals.</step>
      <step>Stale-tool sweep. Search the draft for "Adobe XD". Replace any reference with "Adobe Express" or "Creative Cloud apps with Firefly". Add a note that XD was deprecated in 2023.</step>
      <step>Hybrid check. If the team has both UI/UX and marketing/brand workloads, evaluate the hybrid pattern (Figma + Firefly) and compare its weighted score to the single-tool options.</step>
      <step>Lock-in audit. Estimate library rebuild cost: count components, variants, variables, tokens, and connected files. Multiply by a realistic rebuild factor and require human sign-off on the estimate.</step>
      <step>Enterprise gate. Before recommending to an enterprise buyer, verify SSO (SAML/OIDC), SCIM provisioning, data residency, and audit-log access for the chosen platform.</step>
      <step>Pricing verification. Mark every pricing figure as "list price — verify with vendor sales". Do not present numbers to finance until a human has confirmed enterprise quotes.</step>
      <step>Output assembly. Produce: weighted matrix, recommendation, top three risks, migration cost estimate (if applicable), and an explicit "human verification required" footer.</step>
    </how-to>

    <checklist>
      <check>Team intake captured (size, role mix, budget, launch date, current stack, library size).</check>
      <check>Trigger matches a when-to-use case; no when-not-to-use blocker present.</check>
      <check>Weights sum to exactly 100 percent and each delta from canonical has a written reason.</check>
      <check>Each criterion score (1-5) has a cited source with a date no older than 12 months.</check>
      <check>Document contains zero references to Adobe XD as a current product.</check>
      <check>Document contains zero references to deprecated tools (Sketch Cloud beta, InVision, Adobe XD).</check>
      <check>Hybrid (Figma + Firefly) option evaluated when team has marketing/brand workload.</check>
      <check>Library lock-in cost estimated with component/variant/variable counts.</check>
      <check>Enterprise SSO, SCIM, data residency, audit-log requirements explicitly listed.</check>
      <check>Every pricing figure tagged "list — verify with vendor sales".</check>
      <check>Output includes top three risks and an explicit "human verification required" footer.</check>
      <check>Recommendation cites at least one external source from 2025 or 2026 (vendor docs, uxtools survey, public benchmark).</check>
    </checklist>

    <commands>
      <command name="grep-stale-xd"><![CDATA[grep -in "adobe xd" recommendation.md || echo "no stale XD references"]]></command>
      <command name="grep-stale-tools"><![CDATA[grep -inE "adobe xd|invision|sketch cloud beta|framer classic" recommendation.md || echo "no stale tool references"]]></command>
      <command name="check-weight-sum"><![CDATA[python3 -c "weights=[25,20,20,15,10,10]; assert sum(weights)==100, sum(weights); print('weights ok:', sum(weights))"]]></command>
      <command name="open-decision-matrix"><![CDATA[$EDITOR templates/decision-matrix.md]]></command>
      <command name="render-comparison-prompt"><![CDATA[cat templates/prompt-comparison.txt]]></command>
      <command name="render-migration-prompt"><![CDATA[cat templates/prompt-migration.txt]]></command>
      <command name="vendor-pages"><![CDATA[xdg-open https://www.figma.com/pricing/ ; xdg-open https://www.adobe.com/creativecloud/business/plans.html]]></command>
    </commands>

    <prompt purpose="Team-context comparison + weighted recommendation">
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
You are advising a product team on Figma vs Adobe Creative Cloud for 2026.

INPUTS
- Team size: <N people>
- Role mix: <UI/UX X%, brand Y%, marketing Z%, illustration A%, video B%>
- Budget: <per-seat or annual>
- Priority weights (must sum to 100): collaboration W1%, AI features W2%, dev handoff W3%, asset creation W4%, print/brand W5%, enterprise security W6%
- Current stack: <tools, library size in components/variables>
- Enterprise constraints: <SSO required y/n, SCIM y/n, data residency region>

OUTPUT
1. Weighted decision matrix (criterion, weight, Figma 1-5, Adobe 1-5, weighted score). Cite a source for each score.
2. Recommendation (single tool, hybrid, or split-by-role) with one-paragraph rationale.
3. Top three risks of the chosen option.
4. Pricing estimate, marked "list price - verify with vendor sales".
5. Human verification checklist (pricing, SSO/SCIM, library migration cost, feature parity claims).

HARD RULES
- Do NOT mention Adobe XD as a current product. It was deprecated in 2023. Use Adobe Express or Creative Cloud apps with Firefly instead.
- Flag every feature parity claim that requires vendor-page verification.
- Treat all pricing as list pricing; never present a number to finance without human confirmation.
- For hybrid, specify exactly which tasks go to Figma and which go to Adobe.
      ]]></code>
    </prompt>

    <prompt purpose="Structured migration risk report">
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
A team is considering migrating from <SOURCE> to <TARGET> (one of Figma or Adobe).

CURRENT ASSETS
- Component library size: <N components, V variants>
- Variables/design tokens: <count and structure>
- File count: <number>
- Active integrations: <plugins, CI hooks, Code Connect, Storybook ties>
- Roles using the tool: <list>

ASSESS
1. Asset conversion feasibility. For each asset class, mark Convertible / Manual rebuild / Lost.
2. Workflow disruption per affected workflow: High / Medium / Low.
3. Training requirements per role: scope and onboarding effort (qualitative).
4. Cost delta. Subscription delta + rebuild effort estimate (token cost or human-hour ballpark, marked "estimate - requires human review").
5. Top three risks of the migration.

OUTPUT
A structured migration risk report ready to present to engineering leadership. Mark every numerical estimate as requiring human verification. Library rebuild cost is systematically underestimated; require an explicit human estimate based on actual component and variable counts.
      ]]></code>
    </prompt>

    <template path="templates/decision-matrix.md" purpose="Weighted scoring table for Figma vs Adobe across 6 criteria"/>
    <template path="templates/prompt-comparison.txt" purpose="Prompt for team-context comparison and weighted recommendation"/>
    <template path="templates/prompt-migration.txt" purpose="Prompt for structured migration risk report"/>

    <verify>
      <step>Run the stale-tool grep: <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[grep -inE "adobe xd|invision|sketch cloud beta" recommendation.md]]></code> and confirm zero hits.</step>
      <step>Confirm the weight sum equals 100 by running the check-weight-sum command above.</step>
      <step>Open the decision-matrix template and confirm every cell is filled. Total weighted score = sum(score multiplied by weight) for each platform.</step>
      <step>Open <code lang="text"><![CDATA[https://www.figma.com/pricing/]]></code> and <code lang="text"><![CDATA[https://www.adobe.com/creativecloud/business/plans.html]]></code> in a browser and verify the listed prices match the document within the same calendar quarter.</step>
      <step>For enterprise recommendations, confirm SSO (SAML/OIDC), SCIM provisioning, data residency, and audit-log access have each been verified against vendor documentation. Record the verification date.</step>
      <step>For migration recommendations, confirm a human owner is named for the library rebuild estimate. The estimate must reference actual component and variable counts, not generic ratios.</step>
      <step>Confirm the document includes a footer that explicitly lists "human verification required" items: pricing, SSO/SCIM/data-residency, feature parity claims, and library migration cost.</step>
      <step>Cross-check at least one current external source (uxtools survey, vendor blog, public benchmark) dated 2025 or 2026 is cited.</step>
    </verify>

    <warning>Never present any pricing or feature-parity claim as final without human verification. Vendor pricing pages and feature sets change continuously; an LLM-generated recommendation has a verification half-life measured in weeks, not months.</warning>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.figma.com/pricing/"/>
      <link href="https://www.adobe.com/creativecloud/business/plans.html"/>
      <link href="https://uxtools.co/survey-2026/"/>
      <link href="https://www.figma.com/blog/dev-mode/"/>
      <link href="https://www.adobe.com/products/firefly.html"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
